FILL_CH14 = {
  "14": {
    "1": "<p>Iconium was a major city of the Phrygian-Lycaonian border region in central Anatolia, an important node on the road system connecting the Anatolian plateau cities. It had a substantial Jewish community and a mixed Greek-speaking Gentile population. The pattern — synagogue entry → large Jewish and Gentile response → Jewish opposition → forced departure — is the paradigmatic first-journey sequence Luke repeats at each city, establishing a narrative template for the Pauline mission strategy.</p>",
    "2": "<p>Jews who refused to believe (<em>hoi de apeithēsantes Ioudaioi</em>) stirred up the Gentiles and poisoned their minds (<em>ekakōsan tas psychas tōn ethnōn</em>) against the brothers: the construction of organized opposition by the synagogue community against new converts reflects the social dynamics of diaspora Jewish communities. The synagogue held considerable communal authority; its leadership's hostility could translate into civic pressure, economic exclusion, and eventually mob action — precisely what develops in vv.4-5.</p>",
    "3": "<p>So they remained for a long time, speaking boldly for the Lord, who bore witness to the word of his grace by granting signs and wonders to be done through their hands: the apostolic decision to stay despite opposition is notable. Signs and wonders (<em>sēmeia kai terata</em>) authenticating the word is the pattern established at Pentecost (2:43; 5:12) and Philip's Samaritan mission (8:6-7). God's verification through miracles is what enables the mission to continue in a hostile environment.</p>",
    "4": "<p>The city was divided (<em>eschisthē to plēthos tēs poleōs</em>): the gospel's arrival creates social fissure rather than uniform acceptance. The division follows existing social allegiances — some with the Jews, others with the apostles. Luke's use of 'apostles' for both Paul and Barnabas here (and v.14) reflects a broader usage of the term than Luke normally employs (restricted to the Twelve in most of Acts); it acknowledges Paul and Barnabas as commissioned agents of the Antioch church.</p>",
    "5": "<p>An attempt by both Gentiles and Jews with their rulers to mistreat and stone them (<em>hybrisai kai lithobolēsai autous</em>): the coalition of Jewish and Gentile opposition united under civic leadership is significant. The stoning threat uses the Jewish judicial method of execution for blasphemy (Lev 24:14; cf. Stephen); its adoption by Gentile civic rulers reflects the kind of cross-community enforcement that threatened both Roman public order charges and Jewish religious charges.</p>",
    "6": "<p>They fled to Lystra and Derbe, cities of Lycaonia: Lystra and Derbe were in the Roman province of Galatia (Lycaonia region). Lystra was a Roman colony (founded by Augustus) with a relatively small Jewish community. The absence of a synagogue (no mention of one) suggests Paul's initial audience there was primarily Gentile — the healing of the lame man (vv.8-10) serves as the public sign that opens the mission. The Galatian letter likely addresses this region.</p>",
    "7": "<p>And there they continued preaching the gospel: the brief summary before the Lystra healing is Luke's signal that the mission continues despite forced relocation. The plural 'there' suggests itinerant activity across the region; the Lystra healing narrative focuses the mission at a specific moment and place. Lystra was Timothy's hometown (16:1-2), suggesting the visit in chapter 14 produced lasting community roots.</p>",
    "8": "<p>A man at Lystra who was unable to use his feet, lame from birth, had never walked: the description precisely matches the lame man of Acts 3:2 — congenital lameness, never having walked. The echo is deliberate: Paul's healing miracle mirrors Peter's, establishing that the apostolic healing power is consistently channeled through all authorized agents, not unique to the original Twelve. Luke's parallel establishes the equivalence of Paul's apostleship with Peter's.</p>",
    "9": "<p>He listened to Paul speaking. Paul looked directly at him and saw that he had faith to be healed (<em>pistis tou sōthēnai</em>): the capacity to perceive faith is a feature of the healing narratives in Acts (cf. 3:4 — Peter's direct gaze). The faith-as-prerequisite-for-healing pattern echoes the synoptic healings (Mark 5:34; 10:52). The direct gaze (<em>atenisas autō</em>) is the same word used for Peter at the Beautiful Gate — another deliberate parallel.</p>",
    "10": "<p>'Stand upright on your feet!' (<em>Anastēthi epi tous podas sou orthos</em>) — the command uses the same structure as Peter's 'rise and walk' at the Beautiful Gate (3:6). The lame man 'sprang up and began walking' (<em>hēlato kai periepatei</em>): the springing response echoes Isa 35:6 ('then the lame man will leap like a deer'), the eschatological restoration sign. The public nature of the healing in the open square — not a private or controlled setting — maximizes its civic impact.</p>",
    "11": "<p>When the crowds saw what Paul had done, they lifted up their voices in Lycaonian (<em>Lykaonisti</em>): the use of the regional language rather than Greek is a sociological marker — in their excitement, the crowd reverts to the mother tongue. <em>Lykaonisti</em> is the only reference to this Lycaonian dialect in ancient sources; it confirms Luke's acquaintance with regional linguistic diversity. The crowd's reaction — mistaking the apostles for Zeus and Hermes descended — reflects the Anatolian religious environment.</p>",
    "12": "<p>They called Barnabas Zeus and Paul Hermes, because he was the leader in speaking (<em>hēgeito tou logou</em>): in Greco-Roman divine mythology, Hermes was the messenger and spokesman of the gods — a natural identification for the speaking apostle. A local legend recorded by Ovid (<em>Metamorphoses</em> 8.626-724) describes Zeus and Hermes visiting Phrygia (adjacent to Lycaonia) incognito; the story explains the crowd's readiness to interpret miraculous visitors as divine. They are determined not to repeat their ancestors' inhospitality to the gods.</p>",
    "13": "<p>The priest of Zeus whose temple was before the city brought oxen and garlands to the gates and wanted to offer sacrifice with the crowds: the planned sacrifice is a major civic-religious event. Sacrifice before a city's main gate was the protocol for receiving divine visitors. The oxen and garlands (<em>taurous kai stephanous</em>) represent considerable resources — this is not a spontaneous offering but a prepared ritual. The priest of Zeus held both religious and civic status; his involvement signals official municipal participation.</p>",
    "14": "<p>When the apostles Barnabas and Paul heard of it, they tore their clothes (<em>diarēxantes ta himatia autōn</em>) and rushed out into the crowd: tearing garments is the Jewish gesture of horror at blasphemy (Matt 26:65; Mark 14:63). Paul and Barnabas's reaction establishes their Jewish monotheistic identity in contrast to the crowd's polytheistic interpretation. The tearing of garments would have been a strange and alarming gesture to a Lycaonian crowd — its cultural code was legible only within Jewish tradition.</p>",
    "15": "<p>'Men, why are you doing these things? We also are men, of like nature with you (<em>homoiopatheis hymin anthrōpoi</em>)' — the Areopagus speech's natural theology in miniature. Paul's address is calibrated to a Gentile audience with no OT background: he begins with creation (v.15b), divine sustaining providence (v.17), and the call to turn from idols. The phrase 'the living God who made heaven and earth and the sea and all that is in them' is the language of the Shema's expanded form (Exod 20:11; Ps 146:6) — Jewish creation monotheism presented without Jewish cultural markers.</p>",
    "16": "<p>'In past generations he allowed all the nations to walk in their own ways' (<em>en tais parōcheEmenais geneais eiasen panta ta ethnē poreuesthai tais hodois autōn</em>): the acknowledgment of a pre-evangelistic era of divine forbearance parallels Paul's Areopagus speech (Acts 17:30: 'the times of ignorance God overlooked'). This is not moral relativism but the acknowledgment of a salvation-historical shift: the Gentiles' pre-gospel wandering was permitted but is now called to an end by the gospel's arrival.</p>",
    "17": "<p>'Yet he did not leave himself without witness (<em>amartyron heauton aphēken</em>) — he did good by giving you rains from heaven and fruitful seasons': natural providence as preparatory revelation. The catalogue — rain, seasons, food, gladness of heart — reflects the Greco-Roman understanding of divine beneficence (<em>euergesía</em>) as the primary evidence for divine existence. The argument is that creation's regular provision is a form of divine self-testimony (<em>martyria</em>) that should have led the nations to seek the Creator. Paul's Lystra speech and Areopagus speech both develop this natural-theology argument.</p>",
    "18": "<p>Even with these words they scarcely restrained the crowds from offering sacrifice to them (<em>molis katepausan tous ochlous tou mē thyein autois</em>): the resistance of the Lycaonian crowd to Paul's monotheistic correction shows the depth of their polytheistic reflex. A crowd that has witnessed a genuine miracle and identified it as divine action will not easily be redirected from sacrifice. The 'scarcely' (<em>molis</em>) is a realistic detail — the religious enthusiasm of eyewitnesses to a miracle is not quickly dissolved by theological argument.</p>",
    "19": "<p>Jews came from Antioch and Iconium and persuaded the crowds to stone Paul (<em>lithasantes ton Paulon eilkon exō tēs poleōs</em>): the traveling Jewish opponents who follow Paul across cities are a historically plausible group — organized religious opponents with resources for travel, motivated by the disruption Paul causes to established diaspora Jewish communities. The stoning of Paul and the dragging outside the city is the same treatment given Stephen (7:58). Paul lists this stoning in 2 Cor 11:25 among his sufferings.</p>",
    "20": "<p>When the disciples gathered around him, he rose up and entered the city: the prayer-encircling of Paul's apparently dead body by the disciples is the apostolic community's response. Paul's recovery — whether miraculous or natural — is not explained; Luke records that he rose and returned to the city. The courage of returning to the city where he had just been stoned is remarkable. The next day he left for Derbe with Barnabas, completing the forward thrust of the journey before the return arc begins.</p>",
    "21": "<p>After they had preached the gospel to Derbe and made many disciples (<em>mathēteusantes hikanous</em>), they returned to Lystra, Iconium, and Antioch: the return journey retraces the route through hostile territory. The decision to return rather than travel east to Tarsus (Paul's hometown, which would have been closer) shows the pastoral priority of strengthening the new communities. <em>Mathēteusantes</em> (having made disciples) is the same verb as Matt 28:19 — the Great Commission vocabulary applied to the first missionary journey's fruit.</p>",
    "22": "<p>Strengthening the souls of the disciples, encouraging them to continue in the faith, and saying that through many tribulations we must enter the kingdom of God (<em>dia pollōn thlipseōn dei hēmas eiselthein eis tēn basileian tou theou</em>): the 'must' (<em>dei</em>) of tribulation-before-kingdom is the pattern of the Servant's path (Isa 53), Jesus's passion prediction (Luke 9:22), and the Pauline theology of cruciform living (Phil 3:10; Col 1:24). Paul returns to communities he left in persecution and teaches that their suffering is structurally continuous with the apostolic and dominical pattern.</p>",
    "23": "<p>They appointed elders for them in every church (<em>cheirotOnēsantes de autois kat ekklēsian presbyterous</em>): <em>cheirotoneō</em> (appoint by raising hands) was the Athenian democratic vocabulary for election by show of hands; in Jewish communities, elders (<em>presbyteroi</em>) were the established governance structure of synagogue communities. The appointment of elders in each new church replicates the Jewish community governance model in the new Christian assemblies — providing pastoral oversight after the apostolic founders depart.</p>",
    "24": "<p>They passed through Pisidia (<em>Pisidian</em> region in southern Anatolia) and came to Pamphylia on the southern coast. The journey back through these regions without extended ministry stops (unlike the forward journey) reflects the return-arc narrative structure: the cities named are checkpoints on the route rather than new mission fronts. Pamphylia was the coastal province through which they would access the port of Attalia for the sea voyage back to Antioch.</p>",
    "25": "<p>When they had spoken the word in Perga (<em>lalesantes en Pergē ton logon</em>): a brief note distinguishing the return visit (with proclamation) from the earlier passing through (13:13-14, where they passed through Perga without apparent extended ministry). Attalia (modern Antalya, Turkey) was the major port city of Pamphylia — the staging point for the sea journey across the northeastern Mediterranean to Syria. The return sea voyage completes the geographic arc of the first journey.</p>",
    "26": "<p>From Attalia they sailed to Antioch, where they had been commended to the grace of God for the work that they had fulfilled (<em>eis ho ēsan paradedomenoi tē chariti tou theou eis to ergon ho eplērōsan</em>): the commission language echoes the sending scene of 13:2-3. The Antioch church had commended Paul and Barnabas to God's grace; they return having 'fulfilled' (<em>plēroō</em>) the work. The return to the commissioning base for report (v.27) is the protocol for sent envoys in both Jewish and Greco-Roman diplomatic practice.</p>",
    "27": "<p>When they arrived and gathered the church together, they declared all that God had done with them (<em>anēggellon hosa epoiēsen ho theos met autōn</em>) and how he had opened a door of faith to the Gentiles: the mission report uses the standard apostolic attribution — all that 'God had done' through them, not what they had accomplished. The 'door of faith' (<em>thyran pisteōs</em>) metaphor (cf. 1 Cor 16:9; 2 Cor 2:12; Col 4:3) frames the Gentile mission as an opening that God created, not a strategic initiative of the apostles.</p>",
    "28": "<p>They remained there no little time with the disciples: the extended Antioch stay between the first and second journeys is the recovery and consolidation period. Acts 15:1-2 introduces the circumcision controversy that disrupted this period and required the Jerusalem Council. The Syrian Antioch church, with its mixed Jewish-Gentile composition, was both the theological flashpoint for the Gentile-mission questions and the base from which Paul would continue his ministry.</p>"
  }
}

FILL_CH15 = {
  "15": {
    "2": "<p>Paul and Barnabas had no small dissension and debate (<em>staseōs kai zētēseōs ouk oligēs</em>) with the men from Judea who insisted on circumcision: <em>stasis</em> is the word for civic faction or riot — the controversy was serious and disruptive to the Antioch community. The decision to send Paul, Barnabas, and others to Jerusalem reflects the Antioch church's recognition that this question required adjudication by the apostolic center. The authority of Jerusalem over diaspora churches (inherited from synagogue network structure) is both assumed and contested in this episode.</p>",
    "3": "<p>Being sent on their way by the church, they passed through Phoenicia and Samaria, declaring the conversion of the Gentiles and bringing great joy to all the brothers: the informal mission reports along the route preview the formal Jerusalem report. Phoenicia and Samaria had received the gospel in the first dispersion phase (11:19; 8:1-5); their communities' joy at Gentile conversion implies that these communities were already theologically open to the Gentile mission — the resistance came specifically from the Jerusalem-Judea sphere.</p>",
    "4": "<p>When they arrived in Jerusalem, they were welcomed by the church and the apostles and the elders (<em>tē te ekklēsia kai tois apostolois kai tois presbyterois</em>): the triple reception group — congregation, apostles, elders — reflects the Jerusalem community's organizational structure. The apostles are still the senior authority; the elders (introduced in 11:30) are the administrative governance body; the congregation is the communal witness. Paul and Barnabas reported all that God had done through them — the same report format as to Antioch (14:27).</p>",
    "5": "<p>Some believers who belonged to the party of the Pharisees (<em>tines tōn apo tēs haireseōs tōn Pharisaiōn pepisteukotes</em>) rose up and said it was necessary to circumcise the Gentile converts and to order them to keep the law of Moses: the Pharisaic party within the church represents the highest standard of Jewish Torah-observance in the first-century world. Their position was scripturally grounded (Gen 17:10-14 — circumcision as the eternal covenant sign) and had deep theological precedent. The question was whether the eschatological arrival of Christ had modified the covenant's applicability to Gentile converts.</p>",
    "6": "<p>The apostles and elders gathered to consider this matter: the Jerusalem Council's formal deliberation structure mirrors the Sanhedrin — the body of recognized leaders gathered to decide a matter of religious law. The private deliberation (v.6, apostles and elders) precedes the larger assembly (v.12, the whole congregation). The council's decision carries authority not because of its institutional power alone but because James's exegetical argument (vv.14-18) grounds it in Scripture.</p>",
    "7": "<p>After much debate (<em>pollēs de zētēseōs genomenēs</em>), Peter stood and said: the much debate is historically realistic — the question had been contested in the church since at least the Cornelius episode (11:1-18). Peter's intervention carries weight because of the Cornelius precedent: God had already decided the question by giving the Spirit to uncircumcised Gentiles before baptism, without requiring circumcision. Peter's speech translates the Cornelius experience into a theological principle: God himself tested the Gentiles' hearts and found faith, not Torah-observance, as the criterion.</p>",
    "8": "<p>'God who knows the heart (<em>kardiognōstēs ho theos</em>) bore witness to them by giving them the Holy Spirit just as he did to us': <em>kardiognōstēs</em> appears only here and in Acts 1:24 in the NT — it is the divine attribute that makes God's acceptance-verdict final. God's knowledge of Cornelius's household's hearts, expressed through the Spirit's gift, is the evidence that circumcision is not the criterion for acceptance. The argument is entirely from divine action rather than human deliberation: God chose; the council should ratify God's choice.</p>",
    "9": "<p>'He made no distinction (<em>ouden diekrinen</em>) between us and them, having cleansed their hearts by faith' — the cleansing of the heart by faith is the inward reality of which baptism is the outward sign; its occurrence in Cornelius's household before baptism establishes that the inward reality precedes and determines the validity of the outward rite. The <em>ouden diekrinen</em> (made no distinction) echoes Peter's own breakthrough in 10:34 (<em>ouk estin prosōpolēmptēs ho theos</em> — God does not show partiality).</p>",
    "10": "<p>'Why do you put God to the test by placing a yoke on the neck of the disciples that neither our fathers nor we have been able to bear?' (<em>zugon... hon oute hoi pateres hēmōn oute hēmeis ischysamen bastasai</em>): the yoke (<em>zugos</em>) metaphor for Torah-obligation was in common Jewish use (Sir 51:26 — Ben Sira's wisdom as a yoke to bear). Peter's striking admission that the law is a 'burden' the Jewish community itself has not successfully borne reframes the question: imposing Torah-observance on Gentiles is testing God by requiring what God himself has not demanded as the salvation-condition.</p>",
    "11": "<p>Peter's thesis — 'we believe that we will be saved through the grace of the Lord Jesus, just as they will' (<em>alla dia tēs charitos tou kyriou Iēsou pisteuomen sōthēnai kath hon tropon kakeinoi</em>) — is the Pauline soteriology in Petrine form. The reversal is deliberate: not 'Gentiles saved like Jews' (by Torah) but 'Jews saved like Gentiles' (by grace through faith). This is the exegetical foundation that the Jerusalem Council endorses and that Paul will develop throughout his letters.</p>",
    "12": "<p>All the assembly fell silent and listened to Barnabas and Paul as they related what signs and wonders God had done through them among the Gentiles: the assembly's silence after Peter's speech is the rhetorical pause before the evidence. The signs and wonders (<em>sēmeia kai terata</em>) God performed through Paul and Barnabas among the Gentiles are the material corroboration of Peter's theological argument: God himself authenticated the Gentile mission through miracles, just as he authenticated the Jerusalem mission at Pentecost.</p>",
    "13": "<p>After they finished speaking, James replied: James the Lord's brother (identified in Gal 1:19 and 2:9 as a pillar of the Jerusalem church) provides the decisive ruling. His authority in the Jerusalem church by this point (ca. 48-49 CE) is unquestioned — both Josephus (<em>Ant.</em> 20.197-203) and Paul (Gal 2:12) confirm his leadership. His use of 'Simeon' (the Hebrew form of Peter's name) rather than 'Simon' or 'Peter' signals a deliberate formality in the citation.</p>",
    "14": "<p>'Simeon has related how God first visited the Gentiles to take from them a people for his name' (<em>labon ex ethnōn laon tō onomati autou</em>): the language of 'taking a people' from the nations is the election vocabulary applied to Israel (Deut 7:6; 14:2 — 'a people for his own possession'). James interprets the Cornelius event as the formation of a Gentile covenant-people — not Gentiles joining Israel but a parallel act of divine choosing. The phrase 'for his name' grounds Gentile inclusion in God's own covenantal purpose.</p>",
    "15": "<p>The words of the prophets agree with this (<em>toutō symphōnousin hoi logoi tōn prophētōn</em>): James grounds the decision in Scripture rather than in experience alone. The agreement of prophetic Scripture with the empirical evidence (Spirit falling on Gentiles, miraculous signs) is the double testimony that carries the council. James cites Amos 9:11-12 as the scriptural warrant — the passage about rebuilding David's fallen tent to enable the nations to seek the Lord.</p>",
    "16": "<p>Amos 9:11 LXX — 'I will return and rebuild the tent of David that has fallen' (<em>anastrophō kai anoikodomēsō tēn skēnēn Dauid tēn pepokytian</em>): James quotes the LXX version, which differs from the MT at the crucial point. The LXX reads 'the remnant of mankind may seek the Lord and all the Gentiles who are called by my name' where the MT reads 'the remnant of Edom.' The LXX's universalizing translation enabled the application to Gentile inclusion — either a prior translation decision that James finds useful, or evidence that this was the LXX tradition he knew.</p>",
    "17": "<p>The Gentile nations 'who are called by my name' (<em>ep hous epikeklētai to onoma mou ep autous</em>): the application of the divine-name formula to Gentiles echoes the Abrahamic covenant's universal scope (Gen 12:3). James's exegesis reads the Amos passage as anticipating a time when Gentiles would be incorporated into the covenant community under God's name — not by becoming ethnic Israelites but by being 'called by the name' of Israel's God through faith. This is the scriptural grounding for the council's ruling.</p>",
    "18": "<p>'Known to God from eternity are all his works' (<em>gnōsta ap aiōnos</em>): the eternity of divine foreknowledge grounds the current decision in God's eternal purpose rather than apostolic improvisation. The Gentile mission is not a contingency plan arising from Israel's failure but the unfolding of what God had 'made known from of old'. The council's ruling thus aligns with the divine plan rather than creating new policy — it recognizes what God has already decided and acted on.</p>",
    "19": "<p>James's ruling: 'my judgment is that we should not trouble (<em>mē parenochleîn</em>) those of the Gentiles who turn to God' — <em>parenochleō</em> (trouble/burden) is a bureaucratic term for imposing unnecessary administrative requirements. The ruling is not that Torah is wrong but that its full observance is not the condition for Gentile entry into the covenant community. James's authority to render a ruling (<em>egō krinō</em>, 'I judge/decide') is confirmed by the council's acceptance of his position.</p>",
    "21": "<p>James's rationale for the four prohibitions: 'Moses has had in every city those who proclaim him, for he is read every Sabbath in the synagogues' — the ongoing availability of Mosaic instruction in diaspora synagogues means Gentile converts have access to the fuller Torah through communal hearing, without requiring formal conversion. The four abstentions are the minimum Leviticus 17-18 requirements for resident aliens in Israel (<em>ger</em>); by requiring these, James places Gentile believers in the legal category of resident aliens in the covenant community.</p>",
    "22": "<p>Then it seemed good to the apostles and the elders, with the whole church, to choose men from among them and send them to Antioch with Paul and Barnabas (<em>eklesamenois andras ex autōn pempsai eis Antiocheian syn tō Paulō kai Barnaba</em>): the communal decision-making — apostles, elders, and whole congregation together — is the Jerusalem church's governance model. Judas Barsabbas and Silas are chosen as authoritative delegates: their presence authenticates the letter as genuinely from Jerusalem, preventing Paul and Barnabas from misrepresenting the council's position (accidentally or otherwise).</p>",
    "23": "<p>The letter begins: 'The brothers, both the apostles and the elders, to the brothers who are of the Gentiles in Antioch and Syria and Cilicia' — the letter's address covers the Pauline mission territory: Antioch (the base), Syria (the surrounding region), and Cilicia (Paul's home region). The joint authorship — apostles and elders together — reflects the council's institutional structure. This is one of the few actual documents cited (if not verbatim) in Acts, giving it historical-source character.</p>",
    "24": "<p>'We have heard that some persons have gone out from us and troubled you with words, unsettling your minds, although we gave them no instructions' (<em>ois ou diesteilametha</em>): the letter's disavowal of the circumcision teachers is diplomatically critical — it removes their authority claim without naming them. By stating that these teachers had no commission from Jerusalem, the council prevents the Antioch church from feeling required to comply with their demand. The verb <em>diastello</em> (instruct/command) is the word for official directive — they had no official directive.</p>",
    "25": "<p>The letter affirms the decision reached: 'it has seemed good to us, having come to one accord' (<em>homothymadon</em>) — the unanimity-term that characterized the original Jerusalem community (1:14; 2:1, 46; 4:24; 5:12). The delegation of Barnabas and Paul as 'beloved men who have risked their lives for the name of our Lord Jesus Christ' is the council's formal commendation of the first-journey missionaries — establishing their credibility with the Antioch church and beyond.</p>",
    "26": "<p>Judas and Silas are sent to confirm the letter verbally: ancient diplomatic practice required oral confirmation of written documents by authorized messengers who could speak to the document's authenticity and expand on its contents. <em>Diastellō</em> (convey/explain in detail, v.27) — the delegates will provide oral elaboration of what the letter summarizes. The dual channel — written decree plus live messengers — ensures that the ruling cannot be misunderstood or misrepresented.</p>",
    "27": "<p>Judas and Silas will tell you the same things by word of mouth: oral tradition supplementing written documents was the standard practice in both Jewish and Greco-Roman administrative contexts. Letters were often accompanied by trusted messengers who could authenticate, expand, and respond to questions about the document. Silas will become Paul's companion on the second journey (v.40), suggesting his Antioch stay developed into a longer relationship with the Pauline mission community.</p>",
    "28": "<p>'It has seemed good to the Holy Spirit and to us' (<em>edoxen gar tō pneumati tō hagiō kai hēmin</em>): the council's formula for its decision is remarkable — the Spirit and the human council are named jointly as the decision's authors. This is neither pure democratic consensus nor pure charismatic revelation; it is the council's understanding that the Spirit's prior action (Cornelius, the first-journey signs) confirmed what their scriptural deliberation has now ratified. The coupling of Spirit and council is the model for subsequent conciliar authority claims.</p>",
    "29": "<p>The four prohibitions are stated: abstain from things sacrificed to idols, from blood, from things strangled, and from sexual immorality (<em>porneia</em>). Leviticus 17-18 provides the framework: Lev 17:8-9 (sacrifices), 17:10-14 (blood), 17:15-16 (carrion/strangled animals), 18:6-23 (sexual prohibitions). These were the Torah's requirements for <em>gerim</em> (resident aliens) living among Israelites — placing Gentile believers in this legal category acknowledged their covenant participation without requiring full proselyte conversion.</p>",
    "30": "<p>They went down to Antioch and gathered the congregation (<em>synagagontes to plēthos</em>) and delivered the letter: the public reading of the Jerusalem letter before the gathered assembly is the formal promulgation of the conciliar decision. The whole community hears the ruling — not just the leaders. The public character of the announcement ensures broad accountability: the Antioch community is now collectively informed and cannot claim ignorance of the Jerusalem church's position.</p>",
    "31": "<p>When they had read it, they rejoiced because of its encouragement (<em>echarēsan epi tē paraklēsei</em>): the community's joy at the letter signals relief — the circumcision controversy had been a source of serious tension (v.2 — 'no small dissension'). The letter's encouragement is specifically the liberation from the burden of circumcision requirement; the Gentile believers are affirmed in their status without needing to become cultural Jews. The resolution of the first major internal theological controversy in the church produces joy.</p>",
    "32": "<p>Judas and Silas, who were themselves prophets, encouraged and strengthened the brothers with many words (<em>logō pollō pareklEsan tous adelphous kai epestērixan</em>): prophets in the NT had both predictive and pastoral-exhortatory functions (cf. Agabus, 11:28; 21:10-11). Judas and Silas's prophetic ministry extends beyond delivering the letter to direct pastoral instruction. <em>Epestērixan</em> (strengthened) is the same verb Paul uses for his return visits to the first-journey churches (14:22; 15:41) — a standard pastoral care vocabulary.</p>",
    "33": "<p>After spending some time (<em>poiēsantes de chronon</em>), they were sent off in peace by the brothers to those who had sent them: the return of Judas and Silas to Jerusalem completes the diplomatic mission. The 'sent off in peace' (<em>apelythesan met eirēnēs</em>) is the standard Jewish and Christian farewell blessing — shalom / peace — that authenticates the conclusion of a successful mission. The Antioch-Jerusalem relationship, strained by the circumcision controversy, is restored by the council's ruling.</p>",
    "34": "<p>Verse 34 (noting that Silas decided to remain) is absent from the oldest manuscripts (P45, P74, Vaticanus, Sinaiticus) and is a scribal addition attempting to explain how Silas was available to accompany Paul in v.40, after v.33 says he was sent back to Jerusalem. The best reading treats v.34 as a later gloss; the narrative is intelligible without it — Silas either returned to Antioch or was elsewhere in the region when Paul sought a travel companion.</p>",
    "35": "<p>Paul and Barnabas remained in Antioch, teaching and preaching the word of the Lord with many others (<em>meta kai heterōn pollōn</em>): the Antioch church is depicted as a teaching community with multiple leaders — not dependent on any single figure. The 'many others' (<em>heteroi polloi</em>) suggests an active network of teachers beyond the named apostles. The Antioch base of operations, with its mixed Jewish-Gentile composition and prophetic-teaching leadership (13:1), is the model for the churches Paul plants.</p>",
    "36": "<p>Paul's proposal to revisit the first-journey churches: 'let us return and visit the brothers in every city where we proclaimed the word of the Lord and see how they are' — the second-journey impulse is pastoral, not primarily evangelistic. The apostolic mission involves both planting (first journey) and watering/strengthening (second journey). The care for existing communities rather than always pioneering new territory reflects Paul's own self-understanding (Rom 15:20 — he preferred pioneer work but also nurtured existing communities).</p>",
    "37": "<p>Barnabas wanted to take with them John called Mark (<em>Iōannēn ton kaloumenon Markon</em>): Mark (John Mark) had withdrawn from the first journey at Pamphylia (13:13) — the reason is not given in Acts; 2 Tim 4:11 (Paul later acknowledges Mark's usefulness) suggests the break was mended. Mark was Barnabas's cousin (Col 4:10), which explains Barnabas's loyalty. The family connection and Barnabas's characteristic encouragement disposition (4:36) made him willing to give Mark a second chance.</p>",
    "38": "<p>Paul did not think it wise to take with them one who had withdrawn (<em>apostanta ap autōn apo Pamphylias</em>) from the work: Paul's concern is mission integrity — a companion who withdrew under pressure is a liability in dangerous territory. The verb <em>apistanai</em> (withdraw/desert) is the same term used for apostasy in Heb 3:12 — though not implying that level of gravity here, it signals that Paul's objection is to the precedent of abandoning assigned work. The disagreement between Paul and Barnabas is an honest account of a real conflict.</p>",
    "39": "<p>There arose a sharp disagreement (<em>paroxysmos</em>) so that they separated from each other: <em>paroxysmos</em> (sharp contention, paroxysm) is a strong word — the same root as the English 'paroxysm'. The separation of Paul and Barnabas is neither glossed over nor condemned by Luke; it is presented as a historical fact whose providential result was two separate mission teams covering more territory. Barnabas took Mark to Cyprus (his home island, 4:36); the Cyprus mission continues without Paul. Mark's rehabilitation is confirmed by Col 4:10 and 2 Tim 4:11.</p>",
    "40": "<p>Paul chose Silas and departed, having been commended by the brothers to the grace of the Lord (<em>paradotheis tē chariti tou kyriou hypo tōn adelphōn</em>): the commissioning formula mirrors 14:26 (the first-journey commission) — Paul and Silas depart as an officially sent mission team, not as freelancers. Silas's presence as a Jerusalem delegate (v.22, 27) gives the new team both Antiochene and Jerusalem credentialing. The 'grace of the Lord' is the divine resource entrusted to them — the same phrase as Barnabas and Paul's original commission.</p>",
    "41": "<p>He went through Syria and Cilicia, strengthening the churches (<em>epistērizōn tas ekklesIas</em>): the second journey begins not with new territory but with pastoral consolidation of existing communities. Syria and Cilicia were Paul's home region (Gal 1:21 — he mentions missionary activity there between his Damascus conversion and the Jerusalem Council). The 'churches' of Syria and Cilicia are communities that predate this visit; Paul is strengthening what was already there, not planting for the first time.</p>"
  }
}

def main():
    existing = load_comm('mkt-context', 'acts')
    merge_comm(existing, CONTEXT)
    merge_comm(existing, FILL_CH14)
    merge_comm(existing, FILL_CH15)
    save_comm('mkt-context', 'acts', existing)
    total = sum(len(v) for v in existing.values())
    print(f'Acts mkt-context: {len(existing)} chapters, {total} verses.')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
